<br>
Here's a sample of my shading ... don't know how good an example is it as I didn't use a lot of variation.<br>
<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.anyte.20m.com/cgi-bin/i/drawings/ar70.jpg">www.anyte.20m.com/cgi-bin/i/drawings/ar70.jpg</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
<br>
Once I have the line drawing completed, I go in and lightly sketch in the largest blocks of the darkest areas of shading.  I shade using light layers, using the side of my lead to keep the shading smooth.  I build up a couple layers for the darkest area ... then add another layer adding in the next darkest area ... and keep building up in layers until the lightest layer of shading has been completed.  At that point I change to a darker lead and pretty much start the process all over again ... building layers until I've reached the second lightest area of shading.  <br>
<br>
I'm not sure I'm making any sense but to simplify, using the side of the lead as opposed to the point will give you a smoother finish and building layers and blending them as needed will give you more dimension.<br>
<br>
btw .. that drawing was done on white drawing paper ... I shaded the entire paper to get the background.<br>
<br>
Hope this all helps just a little bit.<br>
